[Heading 2] 11.6 Message style
[Normal] The default style should be concise, professional, and calm. The system is not trying to write a viral email or a dramatic pitch. It is trying to write a useful business email that opens a conversation. The tone should be tailored to IT services and consulting language without sounding overproduced. The draft should be confident enough to be specific, but restrained enough to be credible. The CTA should be direct but not forceful.
[Normal] The best emails from this system will sound as if they were written by someone who knows the company's strengths, understands the target company's context, and is comfortable suggesting a sensible next step. That is the balance the platform should preserve in every draft.
[Heading 1] 12. Outlook Integration and Send Control
[Heading 2] 12.1 Authentication and mailbox setup
[Normal] The sending layer should use the company's Outlook mailbox through Microsoft Graph or an equivalent supported Outlook integration. The mailbox connection belongs in settings and should be treated as a controlled credential, not as an invisible dependency. The platform should know which mailbox is active, what account is connected, and what daily sending rules apply to that account. If the token expires or the mailbox is disconnected, the system should surface the problem clearly.
[Normal] This design preserves control because the company already trusts Outlook as the mailer. The platform is not replacing the mailbox. It is organizing the mail flow. That means the draft and queue system should respect mailbox policy, sending limits, and working hours rather than trying to outsmart them.
[Heading 2] 12.2 Draft creation
[Normal] The default email outcome should be a draft, not an immediate send. Draft creation gives the human a final review point and keeps the platform aligned with a controlled outbound process. The draft should be visible in the system before it is written to Outlook, and the system should know which contact and which company each draft belongs to. The draft record should also carry the source snippets and prompt version that produced it.
[Normal] This draft-first approach is important because it prevents accidental sends and protects the company if the AI output needs small corrections. A good draft can often become a great email with one or two human edits. The platform should therefore make editing easy and should never punish the reviewer for taking time to improve the message.
[Heading 2] 12.3 Send queue and rate limiting
[Normal] Approved drafts should move into a send queue. The queue should enforce daily and hourly limits so the mailbox is not overloaded and deliverability remains under control. The system should also honor a working-hours window. If a draft is approved outside the send window, it should wait until the allowed time. Queue items should show their current state clearly: pending, scheduled, sent, failed, or paused.
[Normal] The queue should be simple enough to trust. A user should be able to see what is waiting, what is already scheduled, what failed, and what needs attention. The platform should not try to be clever by hiding queue state behind a single "active" label. Clear queue status is what makes the system feel stable.
[Heading 2] 12.4 Follow-ups and pause controls
[Normal] The system should support a small sequence: an initial email plus up to two follow-ups. Follow-ups should only continue if there is no reply, bounce, or suppression trigger. The intervals between messages should be configurable but not overly complex. A short, understandable sequence is more useful than a sprawling automation tree. Follow-ups are there to support persistence, not to create noise.
[Normal] A one-click pause-all control should exist and should immediately stop new sends from leaving the queue. That control is essential for safety. If the team notices an issue with a template, a mailbox, or a segmentation rule, they should be able to stop the flow instantly. Resuming should require an intentional action. The system should also automatically pause a lead when a strong negative reply, an unsubscribe, or a bounce is detected.
[Heading 1] 13. Reply, Bounce, and Suppression Management
[Heading 2] 13.1 Reply synchronization
[Normal] Incoming replies should be matched to the correct contact using threading or message identifiers whenever possible. The system should not rely only on subject lines or manual searches. Once a reply is linked, the lead should move into a replied state and the message should be visible to the reviewer. The system should also support a small number of automatic reply categories where the signal is obvious, such as out-of-office and unsubscribe.
[Normal] For anything else, the safest path is to mark the contact as replied and let a human interpret the content. The system should not pretend to understand every reply. A simple reply marker with a review path is better than a brittle classifier that mislabels important responses. The team can always add more automation later if the data proves it is safe.
[Heading 2] 13.2 Bounce handling
[Normal] Bounces should immediately remove the contact from future sends and add the event to the contact's history. The bounce should also feed the email health score so the system learns that the address is risky or invalid. Bounce handling is not just about avoiding one failed email. It is about protecting the quality of the list. Over time, bounce history is one of the strongest practical indicators of whether a record belongs in the active send set.
[Normal] The bounce event should be visible both in the lead view and in the reporting layer. If the bounce rate spikes, the team should know. If one batch contains unusually many bounces, the batch should be easy to identify. The bounce system should therefore function as both a suppression mechanism and a diagnostic mechanism.
[Heading 2] 13.3 Suppression logic
[Normal] Suppression should be permanent for unsubscribes and clearly negative responses. If a recipient says stop, the platform should respect that immediately and persistently. Bounced addresses, manual do-not-contact records, and internally flagged suppression records should also be excluded from drafting and sending. Suppression should not be treated as a soft filter that can be ignored by another screen. It should be a hard boundary.
[Normal] Suppression removal should be rare and auditable. If a record is removed from suppression, the system should log who made the decision and why. That protects the company if someone later asks why a formerly suppressed contact was contacted again. A strong suppression model is one of the simplest ways to keep the platform safe and professional.
[Heading 2] 13.4 Health feedback loop
[Normal] Reply and bounce signals should flow back into the health layer. A lead that replied might become more valuable for follow-up or account expansion. A lead that bounced becomes less viable for outbound. A lead that has not been touched in a long time can age into a stale category. These signals should not remain isolated in the inbox logic. They should influence the overall view of the contact base so the system gradually becomes more accurate and less noisy.
[Heading 1] 14. Search, Segmentation, and Lead Scoring
[Heading 2] 14.1 Search and filters
[Normal] Users should be able to search by name, email, company, title, role, industry, location, tags, batch, and current status. The search experience should feel immediate and forgiving. The user should not have to remember exact capitalization or formatting. Search should support both direct lookups and broad filtering so the team can move from a single record to a whole segment without changing screens or tools.
[Normal] For a database of this size, good indexing and careful query design are usually enough. The platform does not need to become a separate search product to be useful. The key is to make common lookup paths fast and predictable. A good internal tool should make the user feel that the records are organized, not that they are fighting the database.
[Heading 2] 14.2 Saved segments
[Normal] Any useful filter combination should be savable as a segment. A segment may be dynamic, meaning it updates as the database changes, or static, meaning it captures a snapshot. Dynamic segments are useful for ongoing account groups. Static segments are useful for a fixed outreach list or a review queue. Both modes are valuable, and the system should support them without complicating the user interface.
[Normal] Saved segments are one of the easiest ways to make the platform feel reusable. If a user repeatedly filters for a certain role, industry, company size, or capability fit, that work should be preserved. The system should make it easy to return to high-value lists without rebuilding the search every time.
[Heading 2] 14.3 Lead scoring
[Normal] Lead scoring should be rules-based and simple. The score can reflect company fit, role fit, freshness, engagement signals, and data quality. The score is not a decision maker. It is a ranking aid. A high score means the lead is more promising for outreach or review. A low score means it may still be useful but should sit lower in the queue. The score should be easy to explain so the team can trust it.
[Normal] The scoring engine should not become a complex condition builder unless the business truly needs that level of flexibility. A small set of configurable rules is usually enough for an internal system. The most important thing is that the score reflects the company's actual outreach priorities rather than a generic sales formula.
[Heading 2] 14.4 Bulk actions
[Normal] The platform should support bulk actions such as tagging, segmenting, exporting, suppressing, queueing, and status updates. These actions should respect permissions and should create audit entries. Bulk action support is important because the data volume is high, and a large part of the team's work will be list-level work rather than individual-record work. At the same time, bulk actions should always show the user what is about to happen before the system executes them.
[Heading 1] 15. User Experience and Operating Screens
[Heading 2] 15.1 Dashboard
[Normal] The dashboard should be the first place the team looks to understand the state of the system. It should show imported batches, duplicates waiting for review, leads ready for drafting, drafts waiting for approval, emails sent, replies received, bounces, suppressions, and current health counts. The dashboard should not try to tell every story. It should highlight the operational signals that matter right now.
[Normal] A good dashboard for this system is not decorative. It is operational. It should help the user answer questions such as whether the last import went cleanly, whether the queue is backed up, whether bounce rate is rising, and whether any review queues need attention. The goal is to reduce uncertainty, not to add chart clutter.
[Heading 2] 15.2 Lead list
[Normal] The lead list should be the central working screen. It should show the person, company, role, status, email health, score, source batch, and key actions. The user should be able to open a lead, inspect history, edit fields, review company context, and trigger draft generation from the same place. The list should support quick scanning and batch operations because that is where the volume lives.
[Normal] The lead list should also make errors obvious. If a lead is risky, suppressed, or duplicated, the user should see it immediately. The platform should not bury problems beneath too many columns or too much empty space. The best list views are compact, fast, and informative.
[Heading 2] 15.3 Company view
[Normal] The company view should consolidate all contacts, company notes, research cards, capability angles, and prior outreach history for one account. This is the place to understand whether the company is a real target and how the company story is evolving. The team should be able to see which contacts belong to the company, what the current message angle is, and whether the account has already been touched.
[Normal] The company view is also the right place to add internal notes after a call or a research pass. If someone learns that a company is actively evaluating a certain problem, that note should become visible to everyone else working the account. This keeps account intelligence from living only in inbox memories.
